                                 |CKBCOLOR
                                 |BKB=======

|WKOThis documentation is meant to teach an easy way to add ansi to your current
code on Darkwind.  There are a few methods.  

|CKBAdding color to items:

     |WKOYou can add color to items very easily. Simple use:
     
     |WKOset_color(|(colorcode);
     
|BKBExample: |XXOset_color(|XX0||XX0B|XX0K|XX00);
|WKOThis would return the set_short in the item as |BKOblue|WKO

|CKBAdding color to a write/say:

|WKOIf you are trying to write the
color of a certain object (that should already have a color), then you can
do something like this:
 
  |XXOwrite(this_object()->query_color() + this_object()->short() + "\n");
 
|WKOHowever, if you want to specify a color, you should do this:
 
  |XXOwrite("|XX0||XX0B|XX0K|XX00" + this_object()->short() + "\n");|XX0
 
|WKOWhen you use the second method, you must always use the format |XYZ.
The color change must also be at the beginning of the string.  You may
have only 1 color change per write/say/whatever.  If you wish to have
part of a line a different color than the rest of the line, break up the
string into two writes/says without a \n in the first one (see second
Butthead example below).  Color changes don't work well with sprintf.
Use write("|XYZ" + sprintf(whatever)) instead.  |RKBDon't attempt to colorize
monsters.|WKO

 
X == Foreground color.  Y == Background color. 
Valid Colors:  Red = |RKBR|WKO, Green = |GKBG|WKO, Blue = |BKBB|WKO, Black = |KKBK|WKO, Yellow = |YKBY|WKO,
               Cyan = |CKBC|WKO, White = |WKBW|WKO, Magenta = |MKBM|WKO.
Z == Effect.  (Bold = B, Underscore = U, None = 0)

You can see the full list of colors via |MKO'colorlist'|WKO
 
|BKBExamples:|WKO
  
  write("|XX0||XX0C|XX0Y|XX0BButthead.\n");|XX0
 
  write("|XX0||XX0G|XX0B|XX0U" + "    " + this_object->short() + "\n");|XX0
 
  write("|XX0||XX0C|XX0K|XX0BButt");|XX0
  write("|XX0||XX0G|XX0K|XX0Bhead.\n");|XX0
 
|YKOThe spaces after the color, before the short, will not be affected by the color.